    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "02f8d81b_2d44a6c8",
        "filename": "src/chromiumos/tast/common/host/host.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 55,
      "author": {
        "id": 1196209
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-08-24T22:02:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I personally have a great fondness for the interface on top of rsync\u0027s src and dst. From the manpage:\n\n              rsync -avz foo:src/bar /data/tmp\n\n       This would recursively transfer all files from the directory src/bar on\n       the  machine foo into the /data/tmp/bar directory on the local machine.\n...\n       A  trailing slash on the source changes this behavior to avoid creating\n       an additional directory level at the destination.  You can think  of  a\n       trailing / on a source as meaning \"copy the contents of this directory\"\n       as opposed to \"copy the directory by  name\",  but  in  both  cases  the\n       attributes  of the containing directory are transferred to the contain‐\n       ing directory on the destination.  In other words, each of the  follow‐\n       ing  commands copies the files in the same way, [...]:\n\n              rsync -av /src/foo /dest\n              rsync -av /src/foo/ /dest/foo\n\nWhen there are conflicts, the default behavior is that rsync:\n* will *not* replace directories with a *file* of the same name (thereby deleting the directory), and\n* will replace files with files of the same name\n\nThere are three flags that changes this behavior:\n\n            --ignore-existing       skip updating files that exist on receiver\n        -u, --update                skip files that are newer on the receiver (by mtime)\n            --force                 force deletion of dirs even if not empty\n\nI don\u0027t think that we really need to worry about --update and --force. Perhaps something like --ignore-existing would be worthwhile, though. A bool parameter?\n\nPerhaps also merge PutFile and PutTree into \"PutPath\".",
      "parentUuid": "d1ea1841_8dd3cd64",
      "revId": "fb4f7f5913348340bdcd63d50947961a284c0156",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ff745ec4_98974d5c",
        "filename": "src/chromiumos/tast/common/host/host.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 55,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000042
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-08-26T01:38:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "one of my motivations, which i should\u0027ve been more upfront about, is avoiding round trips (in the form of extra commands) as much as possible.\n\nin the case of PutTree, i\u0027m just running sha1sum to figure out what needs to be copied and then creating the parent dir and running tar -x in a second command (and see also the TODO in ssh.go about possibly skipping sha1sum for small files).\n\nthe one downside to PutTree is that it doesn\u0027t support renaming files. i don\u0027t think i actually depend on this anymore (i did at one point), though, so it\u0027s probably best for me to use it everywhere and just get rid of PutFile.\n\nthe semantics of PutTree seem pretty simple (it overwrites matching files, except gnu tar seems buggy: https://goto.google.com/lhjgy), and dropping PutFile avoids confusing people with differences between its behavior and GetFile\u0027s.\n\nit\u0027s more straightforward to make GetFile behave similarly to rsync (or whatever), since i don\u0027t care about the number of operations that get performed on the local side. i don\u0027t love rsync\u0027s handling of trailing slashes, though, because i feel like it\u0027s quite subtle and particularly easy to get wrong when it\u0027s surrounded by other functions that behave differently. i think i\u0027m leaning towards making GetFile also replace the dest file/dir to match PutTree\u0027s behavior.\n\ndoes that sound okay?",
      "parentUuid": "02f8d81b_2d44a6c8",
      "revId": "fb4f7f5913348340bdcd63d50947961a284c0156",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
